question: For how many integers $n$ does the expression\[\sqrt{ rac{\log (n^2) - (\log n)^2}{\log n - 3}}\]represent a real number, where log denotes the base $10$ logarithm?  $ A) 900  B) 2 C) 902  D) 2   E) 901$

How many nonempty subsets $B$ of $\{0, 1, 2, 3, \dots, 12\}$ have the property that the number of elements in $B$ is equal to the least element of $B$? For example, $B = \{4, 6, 8, 11\}$ satisfies the condition.  $ A) 256 B) 136 C) 108 D) 144 E) 156$

In the $xy$-plane, a circle of radius $4$ with center on the positive $x$-axis is tangent to the $y$-axis at the origin, and a circle with radius $10$ with center on the positive $y$-axis is tangent to the $x$-axis at the origin. What is the slope of the line passing through the two points at which these circles intersect?  $ A) \dfrac{2}{7} B) \dfrac{3}{7}  C) \dfrac{2}{\sqrt{29}}  D) \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{29}}  E) \dfrac{2}{5}$
What is the maximum area of an isosceles trapezoid that has legs of length $1$ and one base twice as long as the other?  $ A)  rac 54  B)  rac 87  C)  rac{5\sqrt2}4  D)  rac 32   E)  rac{3\sqrt3}4$

For complex numbers $u=a+bi$ and $v=c+di$, define the binary operation $\otimes$ by\[u\otimes v=ac+bdi.\]Suppose $z$ is a complex number such that $z\otimes z=z^{2}+40$. What is $|z|$?  $ A) 2 B) 5 C) \sqrt{5} D) \sqrt{10} E) 5\sqrt{2}$
For how many ordered pairs $(a,b)$ of integers does the polynomial $x^3+ax^2+bx+6$ have $3$ distinct integer roots?  $ A) 5 B) 6 C) 8 D) 7 E) 4$
In Coinland, there are three types of coins, each worth $6, 10,$ and $15.$ What is the sum of the digits of the maximum amount of money that is impossible to have?  $ A) 8 B) 10 C) 7 D) 11 E) 9$

Triangle $ABC$ has side lengths in arithmetic progression, and the smallest side has length $6.$ If the triangle has an angle of $120^\circ,$ what is the area of $ABC$?  $ A) 12\sqrt{3} B) 8\sqrt{6} C) 14\sqrt{2} D) 20\sqrt{2} E) 15\sqrt{3}$

ï»¿Last academic year Yolanda and Zelda took different courses that did not necessarily administer the same number of quizzes during each of the two semesters. Yolanda's average on all the quizzes she took during the first semester was $3$ points higher than Zelda's average on all the quizzes she took during the first semester. Yolanda's average on all the quizzes she took during the second semester was $18$ points higher than her average for the first semester and was again $3$ points higher than Zelda's average on all the quizzes Zelda took during her second semester. Which one of the following statements cannot possibly be true?  $ A) $ Yolanda's quiz average for the academic year was $22$ points higher than Zelda's.  $ B) $ Zelda's quiz average for the academic year was higher than Yolanda's.  $ C) $ Yolanda's quiz average for the academic year was $3$ points higher than Zelda's.  $ D) $ Zelda's quiz average for the academic year equaled Yolanda's.  $ E) $ If Zelda had scored $3$ points higher on each quiz she took, then she would have had the same average for the academic year as Yolanda.

Cyrus the frog jumps $2$ units in a direction, then $2$ more in another direction. What is the probability that he lands less than $1$ unit away from his starting position?  $ A) ~ rac{1}{6} B) ~ rac{1}{5} C) ~ rac{\sqrt{3}}{8} D) ~ rac{\arctan  rac{1}{2}}{\pi} E) ~ rac{2\arcsin  rac{1}{4}}{\pi}$

A lampshade is made in the form of the lateral surface of the frustum of a right circular cone. The height of the frustum is $3\sqrt3$ inches, its top diameter is $6$ inches, and its bottom diameter is $12$ inches. A bug is at the bottom of the lampshade and there is a glob of honey on the top edge of the lampshade at the spot farthest from the bug. The bug wants to crawl to the honey, but it must stay on the surface of the lampshade. What is the length in inches of its shortest path to the honey?  $ A) 6 + 3\pi B) 6 + 6\pi C) 6\sqrt3  D) 6\sqrt5  E) 6\sqrt3 + \pi$

A real-valued function $f$ has the property that for all real numbers $a$ and $b,$\[f(a + b)  + f(a - b) = 2f(a) f(b).\]Which one of the following cannot be the value of $f(1)?$  $ A) 0  B) 1  C) -1  D) 2  E) -2$
When $n$ standard six-sided dice are rolled, the product of the numbers rolled can be any of $936$ possible values. What is $n$?  $ A) ~6 B) ~8 C) ~9 D) ~10 E) ~11$
